<subSubSection id="FC8E653B876DB13719E254E9FCC9FBF5" pageId="34" pageNumber="227" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="B42B36B0876DB13719E254E9FB4FFCB9" blockId="34.[699,1291,763,1189]" pageId="34" pageNumber="227">
<emphasis id="86E0EAA2876DB13719E254E9FCC3FCE1" bold="true" box="[699,855,763,796]" pageId="34" pageNumber="227">Taxonomy.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="73944D33876DB137182954E9FC94FCB9" authority="Woodhouse, 1853" authorityName="Woodhouse" authorityYear="1853" class="Mammalia" family="Heteromyidae" genus="Dipodomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="34" pageNumber="227" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ordii">Dipodomys ordii Woodhouse, 1853</taxonomicName>
, 
<materialsCitation id="04FC3CED876DB13718495539FB4FFCB9" ID-GBIF-Occurrence="3802894354" box="[784,1243,811,836]" pageId="34" pageNumber="227">El Paso, El Paso Co., Texas, USA.</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B42B36B0876DB13719E55558FCC9FBF5" blockId="34.[699,1291,763,1189]" pageId="34" pageNumber="227">
Based on molecular sequence analyses, 
<taxonomicName id="73944D33876DB13719E55563FCB0FC6F" authorityName="Woodhouse" authorityYear="1853" box="[700,804,881,914]" class="Mammalia" family="Heteromyidae" genus="Dipodomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="34" pageNumber="227" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ordii">D. ordii</taxonomicName>
1s a member of the 
<taxonomicName id="73944D33876DB1371F3A5563FB08FC6F" authorityName="Woodhouse" authorityYear="1853" box="[1123,1180,881,914]" class="Mammalia" family="Heteromyidae" genus="Dipodomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="34" pageNumber="227" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ordii">ordii</taxonomicName>
species group along with 
<taxonomicName id="73944D33876DB1371895558AFBEAFC44" authorityName="True" authorityYear="1889" box="[972,1150,920,953]" class="Mammalia" family="Heteromyidae" genus="Dipodomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="34" pageNumber="227" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="compactus">D. compactus</taxonomicName>
, which it closely resembles. Thirty-two subspecies recognized.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
